Have you used mainly Structural Pylon in the construction of your car? Because it has a bit of disconnect-decoupler power, it must be a good show, trying to accelerate , post some pics.

I'm having a bit of an issue with a rover I'm building just now. The vehicle uses both bilateral and angular symmetry, so I built the main body in the VAB before switching over to SPH to add the wheels and supporting structure. When I go to test drive it though, the parts with bilateral symmetry start duplicating as in the picture below.

I'm guessing it's been caused somehow by moving the .craft file across from the VAB to SPH folder. Is there an easy way to fix this, or do I need to strip it down and start again?

The most stable rover I've ever built.

The white blocks are counter weights, 3 tons each (from LLL) which makes the thing amazingly stable.

Lunokhod. Find it at OKB-1 Energia in rocket builders

It's a very capable rover because of the 8 wheels, it has the traction and battery power for prolonged steep climbing.

On Kerbin, it can drive up any side of the launch pad at about 2m/s

On the Mun it can climb hills like this:

The camera in this picture is oriented so that the bottom of the picture is the direction of gravity, at the time of this picture Lunokhod was going up a 45 degree slope at 5m/s
